'''Apparent life-threatening events''' ('''ALTE'''), also known as a '''brief resolved unexplained event''' ('''BRUE''') is when a [[Infant|baby]] for less than a minute has one or more of [[cyanosis|bluish skin]], poor [[breathing]], [[weakness]], or poor responsiveness.<ref name=APP2016/> By the time they are assessed in a [[Health care|healthcare]] environment they must be back to normal.<ref name=APP2016/>
==Treatment== Treatment involves possibly doing an [[Electrocardiography|ECG]] and watching the child for a period of time.<ref name=APP2016/> [[Pertussis]] testing may also be done.<ref name=APP2016/> Other tests are not typically recommended.<ref name=APP2016>{{cite journal|title=Brief Resolved Unexplained Events (Formerly Apparent Life-Threatening Events) and Evaluation of Lower-Risk Infants|date=Apr 2016|url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/early/2016/04/21/peds.2016-0590}}</ref>
